binder_list.body:
The US ambassador to Libya and three other embassy staff have been killed in a rocket attack in the Libyan city of Benghazi.

Libya's Deputy Prime Minister Mustafa Abu Shagour confirmed on Twitter that Christopher Stevens was killed and said he condemned "the cowardly act of attacking the US consulate".

The Libyan official said the US ambassador had been on his way to a safer venue after protesters attacked the US Consulate in Benghazi and opened fire, killing a staff member, in protest at a US film that they deemed blasphemous to the Prophet Muhammad.

The official said the ambassador and three other staff were killed when gunmen fired rockets at his car.

He said the US Embassy had sent a military plane to transport the bodies to Tripoli to fly them to the United States.

Asked about the deaths, a US Embassy employee in Tripoli said: "We have no information regarding this." The employee said the embassy could confirm the death of one person.

Gunmen assaulted the Benghazi compound, clashing with Libyan security forces, who withdrew under heavy fire.
binder_list.headline: US ambassador to Libya killed in attack
binder_list.leadin: The US ambassador to Libya and three other embassy staff have been killed in a rocket attack in the Libyan city of Benghazi.

binder_list.body:
Germany's Federal Constitutional Court has refused to issue an injunction which would have blocked ratification of Europe's permanent rescue fund, the European Stability Mechanism.

The ruling effectively decides that Germany can participate in the ESM, that was set up to support countries in financial trouble and which cannot function without German involvement.

While the judges have cleared the way for the ESM to become law, they have also applied conditions.

The judgment has stipulated that if the German contribution to the fund exceeds €190 billion, the German parliament must approve it.

Later this morning, German Chancellor Angela Merkel is due to address Germany's lower house, the Bundestag, on the court's decision.

European markets rose following the decision and Italian and Spanish borrowing costs fell.
binder_list.headline: German court refuses call to block euro fund
binder_list.leadin: Germany's Federal Constitutional Court has refused to issue an injunction which would have blocked ratification of Europe's permanent rescue fund, the European Stability Mechanism.

binder_list.body:
Tánaiste Eamon Gilmore has said there will be no “unilateral withdrawal” by the Government from the Croke Park Agreement, indicating it could jeopardise a follow-up to the deal.

Speaking on RTÉ’s Morning Ireland, Eamon Gilmore said the deal was constantly under review and that is what was going on at the moment.

There had already been significant pay cuts under the agreement and he said what it did was say there would be no more such cuts, provided there was co-operation in cutting numbers and getting the work done.
binder_list.headline: Gilmore says Croke Park deal will be honoured
binder_list.leadin: Tánaiste Eamon Gilmore has said there will be no "unilateral withdrawal" by the Government from the Croke Park Agreement, indicating it could jeopardise a follow-up to the deal.

binder_list.body:
The President of the European Commission has outlined his vision for the banking sector, in which the European Central Bank would be given supervisory powers over all banks in the union.

Delivering a State of the Union address to the European Parliament, Jose Manuel Barroso detailed proposals for a single bank supervision regime covering some 6,000 European banks.

The plan is a cornerstone of moves towards closer fiscal integration, which EU leaders hope will end years of financial and economic turmoil in the region.

It would require the approval of all member states, however, with tensions already arising between Germany and Britain over the issue.

Germany’s Finance Minister Wolfgang Schaeuble has argued that the ECB should only supervise big banks, who could pose a systemic risk to the financial system. However this was dismissed by Mr Barroso:

A single banking supervisory mechanism is of huge significance to Ireland because such a supervisor has to be in place before the Government can secure a deal on reducing bank debt.
binder_list.headline: Plans for single EU bank supervisor outlined
binder_list.leadin: The President of the European Commission has outlined his vision for the banking sector, in which the European Central Bank would be given supervisory powers over all banks in the union.

binder_list.body:
The families of 96 people killed in the Hillsborough tragedy have begun viewing for the first time thousands of official documents relating to the disaster.

The Hillsborough Independent Panel is overseeing the release of previously unpublished papers from around 80 organisations including the government, police, emergency services, Sheffield City Council and the South Yorkshire coroner.

A report explaining the contents of the documents will be published by the panel, chaired by the Bishop of Liverpool, the Rt Rev James Jones.

The families of the 96 football fans who died in Britain's deadliest sporting disaster are the first to see more than 400,000 pages.

The Liverpool supporters died in a crush at Sheffield Wednesday's Hillsborough stadium on April 15, 1989, where their team were meeting Nottingham Forest in an FA Cup semi-final.

The club today offered an apology to the families and said it hoped the documents would bring them "closure".
binder_list.headline: Victims' families view Hillsborough papers
binder_list.leadin: The families of 96 people killed in the Hillsborough tragedy have begun viewing for the first time thousands of official documents relating to the disaster.

binder_list.body:
Two fires in factories in Pakistan have left at least 261 people dead.

A blaze at a garment factory in Karachi left an estimated 236 people dead, while another fire in a shoe factory in Lahore killed at least 25 people, according to police and government officials said.

Senior Superintendent of Police Amir Farooqi said that police were raiding parts of Karachi to search for the factory owners after the fire there.

Mr Farooqi said 35 people were injured in the garment factory fire and bodies were still being recovered from the facility, which employed about 450 people.

The cause of the garment factory fire was not clear.

"Within two minutes there was fire in the entire factory," said factory worker Liaqat Hussain, 29, from his hospital bed where he was being treated for full-body burns.

"The gate was closed. There was no access to get out we were trapped inside."
binder_list.headline: Two Pakistan factory fires leave 261 dead
binder_list.leadin: Two fires in factories in Pakistan have left at least 261 people dead.

binder_list.body:
Dutch voters have a chance to change their country's course in tackling the European debt crisis as they go to the polls to elect a new parliament today.

The election is a tight race between the free-market VVD party of Prime Minister Mark Rutte and the centre-left Labour Party led by Diederik Samsom, with other parties trailing.

Whichever party wins the most seats in the 150-seat Dutch House of Representatives could be able to form the next ruling coalition and choose the prime minister.

Mr Rutte is a close ally of German Chancellor Angela Merkel and supports her budgetary austerity agenda for reining in the debt crisis.

Mr Samsom is closer to French President Francois Hollande, who favours spending to spur economic growth.

Last-minute polls yesterday showed the two parties neck and neck on 36 seats each or the Liberals fractionally in front, with the hard-left Socialists and the far-right anti-immigration Freedom Party fading in third and fourth place respectively.
binder_list.headline: Dutch voters go to polls to elect new parliament
binder_list.leadin: Dutch voters have a chance to change their country's course in tackling the European debt crisis as they go to the polls to elect a new parliament today.

binder_list.body:
A 25-year-old man was arrested in Waterford following an assault at a house in the city early this morning.

Gardaí were called to the house at Scotch Quay around 2am where a man was being held by the occupants of the house after allegedly committing an assault.

When gardaí attempted to arrest the man he kicked a male garda knocking him to the ground.

The garda attended Waterford Regional Hospital where he was treated for a broken arm.
binder_list.headline: Man arrested following Waterford assault
binder_list.leadin: A 25-year-old man was arrested in Waterford following an assault at a house in the city early this morning.

binder_list.body:
A fourth person questioned in connection with the deaths of two men in Kinsale, Co Cork at the weekend has been released without charge.

A file is being prepared for the Director of Public Prosecutions.

Michael Coleman of Ballinclamper, Dungarvan, Co Waterford, and Liam Coffey of Cappoquin, Co Waterford were found dead on Sunday morning.

Three other people who were also questioned by gardaí were also released without charge.
binder_list.headline: Fourth person released in Kinsale deaths inquiry
binder_list.leadin: A fourth person questioned in connection with the deaths of two men in Kinsale, Co Cork at the weekend has been released without charge.

binder_list.body:
Education and children’s rights top the agenda at the final session of the Labour Party's seminar before the start of the new Dáil term next week.

TDs and Senators, who are meeting in Maynooth, Co Kildare, will also discuss the national Broadband plan.

Yesterday's sessions dealt with the Social Protection and the Budgetary situation.

The first session today is about education, with Minister for Education Ruairi Quinn outlining his plans to achieve equality through reform.
binder_list.headline: Child rights, education top Labour think-in agenda
binder_list.leadin: Education and children's rights top the agenda at the final session of the Labour Party's seminar before the start of the new Dáil term next week.

binder_list.body:
Almost 59,000 school students are receiving the results of their Junior Certificate exams.

Numbers sitting the exam have risen this year by just over 3%, with numbers opting for the Higher Level Maths paper rising by 7%.

Overall, the results are in line with previous years.

Minister for Education Ruairi Quinn said he hoped the rise in numbers doing Higher Level maths would be reflected in the Leaving Cert cycle.
binder_list.headline: Junior Cert results in line with previous years
binder_list.leadin: Almost 59,000 school students are receiving the results of their Junior Certificate exams.

binder_list.body:
The Police Service of Northern Ireland has said it is monitoring a page on social networking site Facebook, which claims to identify paedophiles living in the Limavady area of Co Derry.

Over 1,000 Facebook users have been following the site on which photographs of people from the Limavady area have been uploaded and threatening remarks have been made.

In a statement this morning, the PSNI said they have identified the person behind the page and are monitoring it to ensure it does not breach the law.
binder_list.headline: PSNI 'monitoring' contentious Facebook page
binder_list.leadin: The Police Service of Northern Ireland has said it is monitoring a page on social networking site Facebook, which claims to identify paedophiles living in the Limavady area of Co Derry.

binder_list.body:
PSNI detectives are appealing for information following an assault in Co Antrim.

Police say three men wearing balaclavas forced their way into a house at Carnany Drive, Ballymoney and attacked the home owner with hammers.

A motive for the attack has not yet been established and police say all lines of inquiry will be investigated.
binder_list.headline: Appeal for information following Antrim assault
binder_list.leadin: PSNI detectives are appealing for information following an assault in Co Antrim.

binder_list.body:
The Health Service Executive has issued a warning to drug users about a brown powder form of ecstasy, which may have been a factor in the death of two men in Kinsale, Co Cork.

The HSE has cautioned about the substance in the Cork area known to contain Methylamphetamine, better known as MDMA or ecstasy, and Paramethoxymethamphetamine or PMMA.

It said gardaí have confirmed the product may have been a factor in the deaths of Michael Coleman and Liam Coffey at the weekend.

Medical professionals in the Cork area have been alerted to be vigilant, and the public is advised that the drugs carry serious health risks, particularly when combined with other drugs including alcohol.

The HSE said if someone does get into difficulty after taking the substance, it is important to get help immediately.

Symptoms associated with the powder include high fever, rapid heart rate and agitation.
binder_list.headline: HSE in warning to drug users over ecstasy powder
binder_list.leadin: The Health Service Executive has issued a warning to drug users about a brown powder form of ecstasy, which may have been a factor in the death of two men in Kinsale, Co Cork.

binder_list.body:
Tánaiste Eamon Gilmore has said the Labour Party "is not going to flinch" from the tough decisions ahead.

Mr Gilmore said the party was elected to do a job and it was going to carry out the job of getting Ireland out of the EU/ECB/IMF bailout.

The Labour leader was speaking to journalists before the start of his party's think-in in Maynooth, Co Kildare.

Mr Gilmore said that after five years of crisis, people are feeling worn out, frustrated and worried about what is next.
binder_list.headline: Labour will not 'flinch' from decisions - Gilmore
binder_list.leadin: Tánaiste Eamon Gilmore has said the Labour Party "is not going to flinch" from the tough decisions ahead.

binder_list.body:
Garda Commissioner Martin Callinan has said the number of gardaí on duty has been increased by as much as 25% at certain times of the day due to a new roster system.

Mr Callinan said that a new garda working time agreement had been developed and implemented with the agreement of the garda associations.

He said it was significant because it is the first time that rosters and working times have been changed in over 40 years.

The Commissioner also said the aim now was to match the availability of gardaí and resources with the policing needs of the community, while at the same time protecting the welfare of gardaí.

The new rosters, which ensure there are more gardaí on duty at busier times, have been implemented at no additional cost.

They also allow for shifts to overlap and for greater flexibility by changing shift start times to coincide with the policing of major events, investigations and court appearances.
binder_list.headline: New rosters to put more gardaí on duty
binder_list.leadin: Garda Commissioner Martin Callinan has said the number of gardaí on duty has been increased by as much as 25% at certain times of the day due to a new roster system.

binder_list.body:
The Taoiseach has said the Government is looking at structures within each department in an effort to avoid cutting frontline services.

Enda Kenny reiterated that the Croke Park Agreement would be honoured in full.

He said it had delivered in terms of a reduction in public service numbers and pay, but must do more so frontline services are protected.

The Taoiseach said between now and the Budget every minister is looking at how they propose to get further evidence of the agreement being implemented, in terms of rosters and allowances.

Mr Kenny said the focus of the Government was to provide jobs and restore the economy.

Fine Gael TDs and Senators met today in Co Mayo to discuss political priorities for the coming Dáil session, including the planned referendum on children's rights.
binder_list.headline: Govt wants to protect frontline services - Kenny
binder_list.leadin: The Taoiseach has said the Government is looking at structures within each department in an effort to avoid cutting frontline services.

binder_list.body:
SIPTU President Jack O'Connor has authorised the serving of notice of industrial action on the Dublin Airport Authority in a row over pensions.

The union said it will stage industrial action on Monday 1 October if the dispute is not resolved in the meantime.

Labour Relations Commission Chief Executive Kieran Mulvey confirmed that talks aimed at resolving the dispute over the €700m deficit in the Irish Aviation Pension Scheme for the two companies had been adjourned.
binder_list.headline: SIPTU issues strike notice on DAA
binder_list.leadin: SIPTU President Jack O'Connor has authorised the serving of notice of industrial action on the Dublin Airport Authority in a row over pensions.

binder_list.body:
The Department of Health has said it hopes to bring forward legislative proposals later this year, or early in 2013, to allow cannabis-based medicinal products to be prescribed in Ireland.

The Department said that notwithstanding the reluctance to loosen current controls on cannabis generally, its expert clinical advice is that the cannabis-based drug Sativex, "is a valid treatment option".

Sativex is used in other countries for treating symptoms associated with multiple sclerosis.
binder_list.headline: Health Dept proposals for cannabis-based products
binder_list.leadin: The Department of Health has said it hopes to bring forward legislative proposals later this year, or early in 2013, to allow cannabis-based medicinal products to be prescribed in Ireland.

binder_list.body:
US President Barack Obama said the 11 September victims would be remembered "no matter how many years pass".

His words came as Americans marked the 11th anniversary of the attacks in which nearly 3,000 people were killed.

Two passenger jets brought down the Twin Towers of New York City's World Trade Center, another hit the Pentagon outside Washington and a fourth crashed in a field in Pennsylvania when passengers aboard that flight fought back against the hijackers.
binder_list.headline: US will never forget 9/11 victims - Obama
binder_list.leadin: US President Barack Obama said the 11 September victims would be remembered "no matter how many years pass".

binder_list.body:
Paralympic gold medal-winning swimmer Darragh McDonald was given a rapturous welcome at his school in Gorey this afternoon.

The school's 1,600 pupils and staff came out to line the avenue into the grounds as the 18-year-old was driven around in a convertible car.

Darragh addressed the crowd from a balcony and thanked them for their support and encouragement.

He won gold in the S6 400m freestyle in London and came fourth in the 100m freestyle.
binder_list.headline: Paralympic medal winner returns to school
binder_list.leadin: Paralympic gold medal-winning swimmer Darragh McDonald was given a rapturous welcome at his school in Gorey this afternoon.

binder_list.body:
A 31-year-old man has appeared in court in Australia charged with the murder following an assault on two Irish men in Melbourne last month.

David Greene, 30, from Cabinteely in Dublin was one of two Irish men who were attacked at a boarding house in St Kilda East on 26 August.

Mr Greene died in hospital on Friday while Mr Byas remains in a rehabilitation centre. 

Luke James Wentholt, who was originally charged with assault, was charged with murder before Melbourne Magistrates’ Court today.
binder_list.headline: Man faces Melbourne murder charge after assault
binder_list.leadin: A 31-year-old man has appeared in court in Australia charged with the murder following an assault on two Irish men in Melbourne last month.

binder_list.body:
Mortgage brokers have said they are encountering more cases of banks doing deals with customers struggling with unsustainable debts.

In cases where borrowers have homes repossessed and sold, some banks are simply closing the file instead of pursuing borrowers for an outstanding debt.

Michael Dowling, spokesman for the Independent Mortgage Advisors Federation, said he is seeing more cases of banks willing to "park" debts after homes are repossessed.
binder_list.headline: Banks 'more willing' to park property debts
binder_list.leadin: Mortgage brokers have said they are encountering more cases of banks doing deals with customers struggling with unsustainable debts.

binder_list.body:
Bankrupt developer Tom McFeely has been remanded on bail over a debt of more than €24,000 to a recruitment company.

Mr McFeely appeared before Dublin District Civil Court for the case involving a debt to MCR Personnel.

He was facing up to three months jail for failing to comply with repayments as part of an instalments order by the court.

A warrant was issued on a previous occasion for his arrest when he failed to appear.

MCR's counsel Benedict O'Floinn said Mr McFeely's bankruptcy had no impact in the court process.

An application was being made to vary the instalment order which MCR could not consent to but could not resist.

The court heard Mr McFeely would furnish a statement of means to the court.

Judge Michael Coughlan remanded him on bail to 16 October.
binder_list.headline: McFeely remanded on bail over €24,000 debt
binder_list.leadin: Bankrupt developer Tom McFeely has been remanded on bail over a debt of more than €24,000 to a recruitment company.

binder_list.body:
Gunmen and security forces clashed at the US consulate office in the eastern Libyan city of Benghazi as the armed group protested over a film being produced in the United States.

The incident followed a protest in neighbouring Egypt where demonstrators scaled the walls of the US embassy, tore down the American flag and burned it during a protest over what they said was a film that insulted Prophet Mohammed.

A US embassy source said there had been "an attack" on the diplomatic office in Benghazi, but gave no further details.
binder_list.headline: Clashes at US consulate in Benghazi
binder_list.leadin: Gunmen and security forces clashed at the US consulate office in the eastern Libyan city of Benghazi as the armed group protested over a film being produced in the United States.

binder_list.body:
A 35-year-old man been charged with impeding the apprehension or prosecution of a person charged with murder.

Dublin District Court heard that Anthony Locke, of no fixed abode, allegedly cleaned the scene at a house in Prussia Street in Dublin, where Christopher Jackson died, and subsequently concealed the body.

Detective Sergeant Denis Ellor told the court that he arrested Mr Locke at Mountjoy Garda Station at 9.05pm last night and when he was charged he replied "I am not guilty".

Gardaí objected to bail on a number of grounds and Judge Patricia McNamara refused the application.

She granted Mr Locke free legal aid and remanded him in custody to appear again at Cloverhill District Court next Tuesday.

Mr Locke’s 39-year-old brother Bernard has been charged with the murder of Mr Jackson, whose body was found wrapped in plastic in a wardrobe at his flat on Saturday afternoon.
binder_list.headline: Second man charged in connection with Dublin death
binder_list.leadin: A 35-year-old man been charged with impeding the apprehension or prosecution of a person charged with murder.

binder_list.body:
A 31-year-old man who attacked another man in a road rage incident has been sentenced to 12 years in prison for manslaughter.

Construction worker Raymond Bates died in hospital after being beaten with a hurley in Dublin in September 2010.

Karl Donohue and Mr Bates got into an argument at a junction near Sandymount in Dublin on 26 September 2010.

Mr Bates fell into a coma and died four days after the attack.
binder_list.headline: Karl Donohue gets 12 years for road rage killing
binder_list.leadin: A 31-year-old man who attacked another man in a road rage incident has been sentenced to 12 years in prison for manslaughter.

binder_list.body:
A 42-year-old woman charged with the murder of her eight-year-old son was medically unfit to attend a court hearing in Co Limerick this morning.

Diane Ward, with an address at Harrison Place in Charleville, Co Cork, is charged with the murder of her son Anthony at their home on 3 September last.

Newcastle West District Court was told she was medically unfit to attend the hearing and a letter confirming this was presented to the court.
binder_list.headline: Woman charged over son's death 'unfit' for hearing
binder_list.leadin: A 42-year-old woman charged with the murder of her eight-year-old son was medically unfit to attend a court hearing in Co Limerick this morning.

binder_list.body:
Afghanistan and the United States have reached an agreement to curb divisive night raids on Afghan homes.

The agreement gives local authorities veto power over planned operations and more say in the treatment of detainees.

The deal is due to be signed later today by Afghan Defence Minister General Abdul Rahim Wardak and NATO's top commander in the country, US Marine General John Allen.
binder_list.headline: Afghan, US govts in night raid deal
binder_list.leadin: Afghanistan and the US have reached an agreement to curb divisive night raids on Afghan homes.

binder_list.body:
Minister for Children Frances Fitzgerald has said the proposed referendum on children’s rights is on track for the autumn.

Speaking on the final day of the special Fine Gael meeting in Co Mayo, Ms Fitzgerald rejected suggestions from former Supreme Court Judge Hugh O’Flaherty that the poll was unnecessary.

Writing in a column in The Irish Independent today, he said the constitution and ordinary legislation already offered adequate protections for children.
binder_list.headline: Children's rights referendum 'on track' for autumn
binder_list.leadin: Minister for Children Frances Fitzgerald has said the proposed referendum on children's rights is on track for the autumn.

binder_list.body:
Sharon Collins, who was convicted of soliciting a man to kill her partner and his two children, has been released from prison.

She had been jailed for six years in 2008 in a case known as the ‘Lying Eyes’ trial.

During her trial the 48-year-old Co Clare woman denied that she was behind an email account titled ‘lyingeyes98’.

Her co-accused, Essam Eid, was also jailed for six years for demanding money with menace and handling stolen property.

Eid's sentence was backdated and he was released last year.

There was no comment from the prison service on her release but  Collins left the women's Dóchas Centre in Mountjoy yesterday.

She is out on temporary release but is not due to return to the prison ahead of the completion of her sentence in December.
binder_list.headline: Sharon Collins released from prison
binder_list.leadin: Sharon Collins, who was convicted of soliciting a man to kill her partner and his two children, has been released from prison.

binder_list.body:
A Fine Gael member of Cork County Council has resigned as chairman of the county's Joint Policing Committee, after admitting he is facing a drink-driving charge.

Councillor Michael Hegarty has also resigned his position as leader of Fine Gael on the council.

It is understood he intends to continue as a Fine Gael councillor.

Cllr Hegarty confirmed to RTÉ News last night that he is facing a drink-driving charge relating to a traffic incident, which is understood to have occurred near his home last month.

He said he did not feel it would be proper to remain as leader of Fine Gael on the council, or as chairman or member of the Joint Policing Committee, while the charge was pending.

Mr Hegarty, from Ladysbridge in east Cork, has been a Fine Gael member of Cork County Council for the past 27 years.

He topped the poll in the Midleton electoral area in the last local elections in 2009.

Mr Hegarty has been the leader of Fine Gael on Cork County Council for the past five years.
binder_list.headline: FG cllr resigns chair over drink-driving inquiry
binder_list.leadin: A Fine Gael member of Cork County Council has resigned as chairman of the county's Joint Policing Committee, after admitting he is facing a drink-driving charge.

binder_list.body:
Three inmates have been recaptured after escaping from Loughan House open prison in Co Cavan last night.

All three were detained last night by gardaí. The alarm was raised at 6.30pm yesterday.

It is understood dog handlers and a PSNI helicopter were used in the search operation.

Two of the men gave themselves up within two hours of the escape.

The third escapee was pursued on the northern side of the border, but was eventually arrested in the Republic by gardaí.

The escapes are the latest embarrassment for the Irish Prison Service.

Martin McDermott fled from the unit in March just 12 days after being transferred there.

McDermott was jailed for seven years last July for the manslaughter of Garda Gary McLoughlin in 2009 after ramming him with a car.
binder_list.headline: Inmates recaptured after Loughan Prison escape
binder_list.leadin: Three inmates have been recaptured after escaping from Loughan House open prison in Co Cavan last night.

binder_list.body:
The South African government is releasing more than 14,000 prisoners to mark the anniversary of Nelson Mandela winning the country's first democratic elections in 1994.

It represents about 9% of the country's prison population.

Another 20,000 offenders, on probation or parole, will not return to prison.

Police Minister Nathi Mthethwa said violent criminals and those jailed for sexual, drug-related and weapons offenses will not be freed.
binder_list.headline: South Africa releasing over 14,000 prisoners
binder_list.leadin: The South African government is releasing more than 14,000 prisoners to mark the anniversary of Nelson Mandela winning the country's first democratic elections in 1994.

binder_list.body:
Medical tests presented to a Turkish court suggest that a waiter accused of stabbing to death two Co Down women is not a juvenile as he claimed, but 22 years old.

Recep Cetin, who is accused of killing Kathy Dinsmore and Marion Graham in a wood near Izmir last August, had told police that he was 17.

If convicted of the crime, Mr Cetin would face a much heavier sentence in an adult court.

However, a judge in Izmir ordered that the tests on Mr Cetin's bone marrow be sent to Istanbul for further examination, following a request by defence lawyers.

It is now unclear when a decision will be taken as to whether Mr Cetin will be tried as a juvenile or an adult.

Baris Kaska, the lawyer for the Graham and Dinsmore families, said a determination could take more than six months, although the next scheduled hearing is on 7 June.
binder_list.headline: Waiter on trial for Turkey killings is 22 - tests
binder_list.leadin: Medical tests presented to a Turkish court suggest that a waiter accused of stabbing to death two Co Down women is not a juvenile as he claimed, but 22 years old.

binder_list.body:
Minister for the Environment Phil Hogan was confronted with a Household Charge protest this evening when he was opening a museum in Co Carlow.

Gardaí say a crowd of around 60 protesters was present, but others say the crowd was in excess of 100.

Gardaí were present and said the incident passed off without any of the protesters getting close to the minister.
binder_list.headline: Protesters confront Hogan over Household Charge
binder_list.leadin: Minister for the Environment Phil Hogan was confronted with a Household Charge protest this evening when he was opening a museum in Co Carlow.

binder_list.body:
Hundreds of people are involved in a search for a 57-year-old woman missing from her home in Tullamore, Co Offaly.

Marian Naughton was last seen at the Grand Canal in Tullamore at 2pm on Wednesday afternoon.

Ms Naughton was a native of Knockcroghery, Co Roscommon, and was working as a senior bank official in Tullamore.

Gardaí say she was wearing a red or pink jacket at the time she went missing.

She is described as being 5'9" in height, of slight build, with shoulder-length black hair.

Inspector Kieran Keyes in Tullamore said gardaí are seriously concerned for Ms Naughton's safety.

Extensive searches are being carried out in the Tullamore area with the help of a large number of people who have travelled from Roscommon.

Over 200 people are involved in a ground search near Tullamore. Sub-aqua divers are also searching the Grand Canal and the garda air support unit is in the area.
binder_list.headline: Search for missing woman in Tullamore
binder_list.leadin: Hundreds of people are involved in a search for a 57-year-old woman missing from her home in Tullamore, Co Offaly.

binder_list.body:
United Nations chief Ban Ki-moon has made a landmark visit to Burma to encourage further reforms and push for an easing of Western sanctions to help normalise UN operations in the country.

Mr Ban's trip was his first since a reformist, quasi-civilian government took office a year ago, ending five decades of authoritarian military rule and thawing Burma’s relations with the international community.

The government, led by remnants of the former junta, has stunned the world with economic reforms and unprecedented engagement with the West, the political opposition and minority rebel groups.

Mr Ban called that progress in Burma – also known as Myanmar - encouraging, but still tenuous.

"I'm much more optimistic and hopeful about Myanmar," he told reporters in the remote capital Naypyitaw, where he was due to meet President Thein Sein and other important reformers.

"Nobody said this was an easy process. This process is risky and fragile. We can't always be unconditionally optimistic, we have to be mindful of this and have to nurture this process."
binder_list.headline: Ban Ki-moon on visit to Burma
binder_list.leadin: United Nations chief Ban Ki-moon has made a landmark visit to Burma to encourage further reforms and push for an easing of Western sanctions to help normalise UN operations in the country.

binder_list.body:
Three RTÉ documentaries have won awards at this year's New York Festivals International Television and Film Awards.

''Prime Time Investigates – Ireland’s Illegal Cigarette Trade'' won a Gold World Medal in the News Programme Best Investigative Report category.

''Somalia – The Children’s Famine'' won a Gold World Medal in the Best Television Social Issues/Current Events category and ''Children Are Our Flowers'' received a Silver World Medal in the Television Documentary Biography Profiles category.
binder_list.headline: Prime Time Investigates wins NY documentary award
binder_list.leadin: Three RTÉ documentaries have won awards at this year's New York Festivals International Television and Film Awards.

binder_list.body:
Three men have been found shot dead in a car on the French  island of Corsica.

The bodies were found in a village near the town of Corte in the north of the Mediterranean island.

Around 12 men have been shot dead in Corsica since the start of the year.
binder_list.headline: Three shot dead in French island of Corsica
binder_list.leadin: Three men have been found shot dead in a car on the French  island of Corsica.

binder_list.body:
Public investment in third-level education in Ireland produces a return that is well above the OECD average.

The OECD's latest Education at a Glance report reveals that men who graduate in Ireland will pay back in increased tax payments and other savings almost six times the amount of public money invested in their education.

This compares to an average of a four-fold return across the OECD.

Women graduates in Ireland also represent greater value for money to the Exchequer than their counterparts elsewhere.
binder_list.headline: Irish graduates offer better return on investment
binder_list.leadin: Public investment in third-level education in Ireland produces a return that is well above the OECD average.

binder_list.body:
Up to 300 asylum seekers are facing uncertainty over their futures following the decision to close their accommodation centre in Galway City.

The Department of Justice has confirmed that many of the residents of Lisbrook House will be relocated to other centres around the country.

Family units face the biggest disruption due to a lack of suitable accommodation available in Galway.

Over 100 families occupy three floors of the former Ibis Hotel, many of them women and children.

The majority are from African countries and have been living in Galway for over four years.

The Reception and Integration Agency said it was working with the HSE to prioritise a small number for retention in Galway, based on medical need.

The RIA said it was making every effort to find suitable alternative accommodation for families in other parts of the country.

However, it accepted that the closure of the centre was a difficult process and one that would cause upheaval for residents.
binder_list.headline: Galway asylum seeker centre to close
binder_list.leadin: Up to 300 asylum seekers are facing uncertainty over their futures following the decision to close their accommodation centre in Galway City.

binder_list.body:
A car bomb targeting Yemen's defence minister exploded outside the prime minister's office in Sanaa, killing at least five bodyguards.

Major General Muhammad Nasir Ahmad was said to be safe following the attack in the capital, which came after the death of a senior leader in the Yemeni branch of al-Qaeda last week.

Said al-Shehri was killed, along with six other militants, in what was called a "qualitative operation" by Yemen's army in the remote Hadramout province.

There were conflicting reports on how Shehri died.

A Yemeni security source said Shehri was killed in an operation last Wednesday that was thought to have been carried out by a US drone, rather than the Yemeni military.

US officials declined to comment on whether a drone strike had occurred.

They described Shehri as one of the most important al-Qaeda-linked militants to be released from Guantanamo, where he was taken in January 2002 after being handed over by Pakistan.
binder_list.headline: Yemen defence minister survives car bomb attack
binder_list.leadin: A car bomb targeting Yemen's defence minister exploded outside the prime minister's office in Sanaa, killing at least five bodyguards.

binder_list.body:
The head of Science Foundation Ireland has said the State will continue to fund outstanding young researchers, despite a shift in funding policy in favour of areas that will have the greatest impact.

Dr Mark Ferguson said he accepted criticism from the European Research Council that Ireland needed to improve its performance in drawing down ERC funds.

Just four Irish projects made the grade in the latest round of ERC funding.

Dr Ferguson said the SFI was developing policies that would encourage and support young researchers applying for ERC funding.

Some prominent Irish scientists have criticised what they say is a shift away from supporting basic or frontier research in favour of projects with a more immediate commercial application.

In response, Dr Ferguson said SFI would focus its funding on areas where it thought the impact would be greatest.

However, everything in those areas, from applied research to basic, would be eligible for funding.
binder_list.headline: Four Irish projects receive European funding
binder_list.leadin: The head of Science Foundation Ireland has said the State will continue to fund outstanding young researchers, despite a shift in funding policy in favour of areas that will have the greatest impact.

binder_list.body:
Qualified candidates are not applying for top civil service posts for fear of being vilified in the media.

The head of the Top Level Appointment Commission, which recruits top civil servants, said the invasion of privacy had been cited as a reason why capable civil servants did not apply for senior posts.

Management consultant Maureen Lynott said what she called the "bashing" and "public lambasting" of how civil servants did their jobs was really dangerous, unfortunate and damaging.
binder_list.headline: Civil service candidates 'fear vilification'
binder_list.leadin: Qualified candidates are not applying for top civil service posts for fear of being vilified in the media.

binder_list.body:
Gardaí have said the results of a post mortem carried out on the body of a 30-year-old man found dead in a house in Waterford last night are inconclusive.

They are waiting on further tests, but have ruled out foul play.

The man's body was discovered by his housemate just after 9.30pm at Bishopsfield in Williamstown.
binder_list.headline: Foul play ruled out in Waterford death
binder_list.leadin: Gardaí have said the results of a post mortem carried out on the body of a 30-year-old man found dead in a house in Waterford last night are inconclusive.

binder_list.body:
China's top leader-in-waiting Xi Jinping, who set off a storm of rumours after not showing up at scheduled public events for over a week, is nursing an ailment.

It is possibly a back injury suffered while swimming, according to sources.

Mr Xi, who is due to take over the presidency of the world's second-largest economy in March next year, has skipped several meetings with visiting foreign leaders and dignitaries over the past week.
binder_list.headline: Absent China VP nursing 'swim' injury
binder_list.leadin: China's top leader-in-waiting Xi Jinping, who set off a storm of rumours after not showing up at scheduled public events for over a week, is nursing an ailment.

binder_list.body:
A man in his 50s was seriously injured in an assault in Co Tipperary overnight.

The incident occurred at Church Street, Cappawhite, at around 12.30am.

The injured man was taken to Cork University Hospital, where he remains in a serious condition.

A man in his late 20s was arrested.
binder_list.headline: Man seriously injured in Tipperary assault
binder_list.leadin: A man in his 50s was seriously injured in an assault in Co Tipperary overnight.

binder_list.body:
PSNI detectives investigating dissident republican activity arrested a man and recovered weapons and ammunition in an operation in Co Down.

The 52-year-old man was arrested when police stopped a car near Hillsborough on the main Belfast to Dublin road.

Two handguns and a quantity of ammunition were discovered.

A number of properties in west Belfast were also searched.
binder_list.headline: Guns and ammunition recovered as PSNI arrest man
binder_list.leadin: PSNI detectives investigating dissident republican activity arrested a man and recovered weapons and ammunition in an operation in Co Down.

binder_list.body:
Ireland plans to raise a further €500m on the debt markets this week.

The National Treasury Management Agency said it would auction treasury bills on Thursday.

It will offer three month bills to investors.

It is the second time this year that it will raise short term debt after it tapped the markets for €500m in July.
binder_list.headline: NTMA announces bill auction for Thursday
binder_list.leadin: Ireland plans to raise a further €500m on the debt markets this week.
